ENTRY            A0588   20260204   20260327   20260327       A130
SUBENT        A0588001   20260204   20260327   20260327       A130
BIB                 10         40
TITLE      Dominance of collective over proton transfer couplings
           in the fusion of 32-S and 34-S with 89-Y
AUTHOR     (A.Mukherjee, M.Dasgupta, D.J.Hinde, K.Hagino,
           J.R.Leigh, J.C.Mein, C.R.Morton, J.O.Newton,
           H.Timmers)
INSTITUTE  (3AULCBR,2JPNKTO,3AULNSW)
REFERENCE  (J,PR/C,66,034607,2002)
REL-REF    (N,,J.X.Wei+,J,NIM/A,306,557,1991)
           Compact velocity filter
DETECTOR   (MWPC,SIBAR) Fusion evaporation residues were
           detected using a compact velocity filter and a hybrid
           detector. The latter consisted of a
           position-sensitive, multiwire, gas proportional
           detector backed with a stopping position- sensitive
           silicon surface barrier detector. The velocity filter
           transmitted the evaporation residues to the detector
           whilst deflecting the intense elastically scattered
           beam particles to one side, where they were
           intercepted by a movable tantalum finger. With this
           arrangement, the evaporation residues could be
           precisely measured at angles as small as 1 degr. with
           respect to the beam axis.
FACILITY   (VDGT,3AULCBR) The 14UD Pelletron accelerator
METHOD     (EXTB) The accelerator provided pulsed 32,34S beams
            (~1 ns wide beam bursts separated by 530 ns)
           (TOF) The evaporation residues were identified by the
           energy deposited in the silicon surface barrier
           detector and the time of flight relative to the pulsed
           beam.
ADD-RES    (COMP) 1.Excitation function and barrier distribution
           compared with exact coupled channels calculations
           performed with the code CCFULL.
           2. Results of the exact coupled channels calculations
           including single-phonon states in 32S and single-phonon
           and double-phonon states in 89Y.
           3. Reduced excitation functions and barrier
           distributions for 32,34S+89Y.
HISTORY    (20030714C)
           (20040114U) Last checking has been done.
           (20260204U) SD: Small corrections in all Subents.
ENDBIB              40
NOCOMMON             0          0
ENDSUBENT           43
